Started by Brewster Rogerson in 1971, the collection contains unique and exceptionally rare plants, as well as historic clematis and the newest hybrids. In 2018 the Rogerson Clematis Collection was awarded full accreditation in the Plant Collections Network, an initiative of the American Public Gardens Association in cooperation with the U.S. Department of Agriculture. C. 'Fairy Blue' CRYSTAL FOUNTAIN C. 'Louise Rowe' Clematis patens from Manchurian seed C. 'Duchess of Albany' C. 'Kimiidera' C. 'Comtesse de Bouchaud' (pronounced "boo-show") C. 'Warszawska Nike' (syn. 'Warsaw Nike') C. 'Arabella' C. 'Betty Corning' C. 'Mayleen' C. 'Semu' C. 'Halina 'Noll' Clematis sp. wild-collected, Anniston AL Large-flowered hybrid seed head C. 'Vince Denny' (potentially invasive in temperate climates) C. 'Bill MacKenzie' Clematis triternata var. variegata (Japan via Hinkley) Clematis alpina 'Pamela 'Jackman' C. 'Hagley Hybrid' C. integrifolia seedling in Test Garden C. 'Daniel Deronda' C. 'Piilu' LITTLE DUCKLING C. 'Walenburg' C. 'Alionushka' C. 'Helios' Our Mission and Board The Friends of the Rogerson Clematis Collection (FRCC) was formed in 2004 to ensure that Brewster Rogerson‚Äôs amazing collection of clematis would be maintained and nurtured over time. Since 2005, the collection has grown from a group of beautiful plants in pots to an assemblage of beautiful plants in a delightful garden. Mission We cultivate clematis and community. Vision Honoring our roots and taking new paths to advance a distinctive garden celebrating an exceptional collection of clematis. The Friends group is guided by a Board of Directors. Officers Amy Chase Herman, President Nancy Gronowski, Vice President Dina Trachta, Treasurer Peggy Wros, Recording Secretary Colleen Keyes, Membership Secretary Directors Sophie Bayard, Volunteer Coordinator Mike Bostwick Diane Harris Agnes Kwan Hilliary Montero Kym Pokorny Other Roles Linda Beutler, Curator Susan Toler, Site Manager Nancy Stanton-Chek, Garden Manager Kathy Hemphill, Librarian Sylvia Hoffman, Bookkeeper History From a Collection to a Garden Brewster Rogerson, founder of the collection, was first drawn to clematis because of their incredible diversity. While still a professor of English at Kansas State University, he bought four vines in 1971 and ended up spending the rest of his life acquiring varieties and species from all over the world. Over the years he became a leading expert in the genus and was a founding member of the International Clematis Society (1984), for which he wrote 100 ‚ÄúClematis of the Month‚Äù articles. In search of a climate conducive to growing as many kinds of clematis as possible, Brewster moved to Oregon in 1981. He initially settled in Eugene. Then in 1987, through the generosity of Bob Gutmann, he was able to house the collection at Gutmann Nursery in North Plains, west of Portland. In 2005, Brewster transferred ownership of the collection to the newly-formed nonprofit Friends of the Rogerson Clematis Collection. When the collection threatened to outgrow its home at Gutmann Nursery, the Friends group was fortunate to find a home with the City of Lake Oswego at Luscher Farm, a farm-park on the outskirts of the city and part of Lake Oswego‚Äôs Parks and Recreation Department. Brewster Rogerson remained actively involved with the collection and the garden until his health began to fail. Brewster passed away at age 94 in May 2015. His dedication and love for clematis created a legacy that is now permanently housed in a beautiful garden for all to visit and enjoy. The Rogerson Clematis Collection is located at Luscher Farm, part of the Lake Oswego Parks and Recreation Department. Clematis Social Nightclub - 21+ Skip to content Search for: Home About Us Dine + Drink Dance Travel Blog Previous Next Clematis Social West Palm Beach‚Äôs Newest Nightclub No strangers to the downtown nightclub scene, Cleve Mash and Mike Mash have been staples of the West Palm Beach nightlife industry for over 20 years. Going down memory lane, Clematis Social started off as the infamous Monkey Club which turned to everyones favorite, ‚ÄúDr Feelgoods‚Äù, and morphed into the Pawn Shop, and now, Clematis Social. IYKYK Inspired by Miami‚Äôs Design District and Wynwood Miami , the Mashes went over the top in transforming Clematis Social into an aesthetic pleasing nightclub that rivals even the best clubs Miami Beach has to offer. The outside mural is painted by Amanda Valdez with the interior illuminating vibrantly under state of the art lighting creating one of the most unique nightclub laser show experiences. With a massive Co2 jet cooling system, club goers can stay cool while dancing to the sounds of the area‚Äôs best DJs. Do you want to dance? Those who enter Clematis Social will be greeted with cages suspended above the dance floor and a pulsating sound system that makes you feel the music to your core. The front bar area features ping pong and large sized chess if you need to take a break. When is Clematis Social Open? Clematis Social is open Thursday through Sunday. Party goers can stay dancing till 4am every Friday and Saturday and 3am on Thursdays & Sundays. Clematis Social is located at 219 Clematis Street, West Palm Beach, FL 33401.¬† If you are looking to host your birthday party on Clematis Street or purchase bottle service at Clematis Social, please contact Evolve Nightlife.
